						<summary>

						<p>On a pillar set up on the bund of Achchanna tank.</p>						

						<p>Annadēva-mahārāja, A.D. 1436.</p>						

						<p>Dated Śaka 13[5]7, <hi rend="italic">Rākshasa, Māgha</hi> śu. 15, Thursday, corresponding to A.D. 1436, February 2.</p>						

						<p>Records the construction of a tank by the chief in the name of his mother, Āryamādēvi and the grant of an <hi rend="italic">agrahāra</hi> and other benefactions for the merit of his ancestors, his son and others. (Published in <hi rend="italic">N.D.I.</hi> Part I, p. 297, Darśi 13).</p>						

						<p>[The first two sides of the inscription are considered by the Epigraphist's office as constituting one inscription while the third side as another (No. 297- A.R. No. 65 of 1956-57). All the three sides are put together as one inscription in the <hi rend="italic">N.D.I.</hi> pp. 27 ff. <hi rend="italic">N.D.I.</hi> reads king's name as Aśnadēva but Annadēva may be correct. The inscriptions (A.R. 64 and 65- Nos. 296-297) are badly damaged and reading and purport unintelligible, while the <hi rend="italic">NDI</hi> has better readings, though not verifiable. Readers are advised to consult N.D.I. Part I, pp. 297 ff.]</p>						

						</summary>
